{{about||the song|Ken Carter (song)|the stuntman|Ken Carter (stuntman)}} {{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}} {{Infobox person | name = Ken Carter | image =Coach_Carter_at_an_interview_in_2014-_2014-08-21_16-05.jpg | caption = Carter giving an interview in 2014 | birth_name = Kenny Ray Carter | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1959|2|13}} | birth_place = [[Fernwood, Mississippi]] | other_names = Coach Carter }} '''Kenny Ray Carter''' (born February 13, 1959) is an American business owner, education activist and former high school basketball coach. Carter attended college at [[San Francisco State]], then [[Contra Costa College]], and finally [[George Fox University]], where he played basketball.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page3/story?page=merron/coachcarter ESPN.com: Page 3 – How real is the reel 'Coach Carter?']</ref> He was portrayed by [[Samuel L. Jackson]] in the 2005 film, ''[[Coach Carter]]''.
==Biography== Coming from an abusive family, Carter was raised strictly on academics, but found a liking in sports. As a basketball coach, he maintained that his athletes must take their studies seriously, as good academic performance would give them access to college and other opportunities in life.
This belief was put to the test when, as a high school basketball coach at [[Richmond High School (Richmond, California)|Richmond High School]], he locked out his undefeated team for not honoring academic and behavioral contracts.<ref>{{cite web |title=Richmond Rebound / High school basketball players hit books, coach lifts his lockout |url=https://www.sfgate.com/education/article/Richmond-Rebound-High-school-basketball-players-2952622.php |website=SFGate.com |date=January 12, 1999}}</ref> While the community was outraged at first, public opinion eventually changed, and Carter was praised for his determined emphasis on prioritizing good values for his team. His approach also bore results: every one of his players at Richmond, where he coached from 1997 to 2002, graduated.<ref>[http://www.georgefox.edu/journalonline/winter05/lockout.html Coach Ken Carter: From Lockout to Open Doors] George Fox Journal</ref> The story of the 1999 season is the basis for the [[2005 in film|2005 film]] ''[[Coach Carter]]'', with Carter played by [[Samuel L. Jackson]].
Carter continues to coach sports teams, except basketball. He coached the [[Slamball]] team [[Rumble (slamball team)|Rumble]]. He led Rumble to their first-ever Slamball Cup victory in 2001/2002. Carter has said that the greatest moment in his life was when he carried the [[Olympic Torch]] for the [[2002 Winter Olympics]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}
Carter has a son named Damien (who played for his father at Richmond, and was portrayed by [[Robert Ri'chard]] in the movie) and currently resides in San Antonio, TX.
In the fall of 2005, Carter proposed opening a boarding school called the Coach Carter Impact Academy in the town of [[Marlin, Texas]]. The school never opened and by 2012, the project had been abandoned.
