{{multiple issues| {{one source|date=December 2013}} {{refimprove|date=December 2013}} }}
'''Orleans Technical College''' (formerly Orleans Technical Institute) is a [[technical school]], operated by the [[JEVS Human Services]] agency, located in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]. They have one campuses located in Philadelphia offering full- or part-time programs with day or evening classes in * Air Conditioning Refrigeration & Heating * Building Maintenance * Carpentry * Plumbing and Heating * Residential & Commercial electricity * Court Reporting (no longer accepting new students) * Human Services
They have been in operation since 1974.
==Awards== Orleans Technical Institute was recently awarded the "Military Friendly School" title from ''G.I. Jobs'',<ref>[http://www.militaryfriendlyschools.com/search/profile.aspx?id=214528&year=2014 Military Friendly 2014 - Orleans Technical Institute]</ref> a magazine for military personnel transitioning into civilian life. The list of Military Friendly Schools honors the top 20 percent of colleges, universities and trade schools that are doing the most to embrace America's military service members and veterans as students.
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Technical schools]]

'''Padraic Jeremiah Kenney''' (born 1963) is a [[professor]] of [[history]] and [[International Studies]] at [[Indiana University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiana.edu/~histweb/faculty/Display.php?Faculty_ID=15|title=Faculty and Research: Padraic Kenney|publisher=Indiana University Bloomington|accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref> Previously, he was Professor of History at the [[University of Colorado, Boulder]].

He is the author of several books on [[East European]] (particularly [[Poland|Polish]]) history and politics; his area of specialization is [[social change]] and [[political change]] in the contemporary world, in particular [[civil resistance]] to [[authoritarian]] regimes and [[democratic revolutions]]. His most recent book, ''Dance in Chains: Political Imprisonment in the Modern World'' (Oxford, 2017), examines [[political prisoners]] and imprisoning regimes from the mid-19th century, in particular in [[Ireland]], [[Northern Ireland]], [[Poland]], and [[South Africa]], as well as the men detained at [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]]. His 2002 work, ''A Carnival of Revolution: Central Europe, 1989'' (Princeton), has been translated into Polish, Ukrainian, Romanian, and Czech. A history of [[post-communism]], ''Burdens of Freedom: Eastern Europe Since 1989'' (Zed Books), was translated into Croatian and Italian.

In 2016, he was president of the [[Association for Slavic, East European, and Eurasian Studies]] (ASEEES).

He is a frequent contributor to the Polish online weekly ''Kultura liberalna''.<ref>https://kulturaliberalna.pl/tag/padraic-kenney/</ref> Other essays have appeared in ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/10/opinion/why-poland-cares-so-much-about-ukraine.html</ref> ''[[The Boston Globe]]'',<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/2014/01/15/party-like/m48VD6tLJrXle3dTDiUJjN/story.html</ref> and ''[[The Denver Post]]''.<ref>http://historynewsnetwork.org/article/6132</ref>

He was awarded a grant under the [[Fulbright Program]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ed.gov/programs/iegpsfra/fragrantees2005.xls|title=FY 2005 Grantees by World Area for the Faculty Research Abroad Program (Excel)|publisher=U.S. Department of Education|accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref>

== Selected publications ==
