{{Infobox person | name = Theos Casimir Bernard | image = TheosBernard showing BaddhaPadmasana.jpg | image_size = | caption = Bernard, practicing yoga | birth_name = | birth_date = December 10, 1908 <!-- Do not add flag icons to place of birth/death, per [[Wikipedia:Don't overuse flags]] --> | birth_place = | death_date = {{death year and age|1947|1908}} | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = | nationality = [[United States|American]] | other_names = | known_for = [[Explorer]], [[author]], expert on [[Tibetan Buddhism]] | education = | employer = | occupation = | title = | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = {{plainlist| * Viola Wertheim Bernard (m. 1934-1938; divorced) * [[Ganna Walska]] (m. 1942–1946; divorced) }} | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }} {{Tibetan Buddhism}}
'''Theos Casimir Bernard''' (1908–1947)<ref>{{cite book|last=Hackett|first=Paul|title=Barbarian Lands: Theos Bernard, Tibet, and the American Religious Life|publisher=Ph.D. dissertation, Columbia University, 2008}}</ref> was an [[explorer]], and [[author]], known for his work on [[yoga]] and religious studies, particularly in [[Tibetan Buddhism]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Theos Casimir Bernard|author=Paul G. Hackett |publisher=[[Columbia University]]|url=http://c250.columbia.edu/c250_celebrates/remarkable_columbians/theos_casimir_bernard.html|date=15 September 2003}}</ref> He was the nephew of [[Pierre Bernard (yogi)|Pierre Arnold Bernard]].
==Biography==
Bernard first trained in law, obtaining a [[bachelor's degree]] in 1931 and embarking on an internship in 1932, but decided instead to pursue an advanced degree at [[Columbia University]].<ref>Hackett, 196–197</ref> There, according to 2010's ''The Madman's Middle Way'', Bernard, who described himself as "the first white [[lama]]", became the first American to write a dissertation on the subject of Tibetan Buddhism.<ref name=Lopez>{{cite book|author=Donald S. Lopez Jr.|author-link=Donald S. Lopez Jr.|title=The Madman's Middle Way: Reflections on Reality of the Tibetan Monk Gendun Chopel|date=15 May 2007|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|isbn=978-0-226-49317-6|page=31}}</ref>
In 1936, he toured India and Tibet with his wife, Viola Wertheim Bernard<ref>{{cite web|website=http://omnipotentoom.com/archives/119|accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref> (half-sister of [[Maurice Wertheim]]), studying [[Tantric Yoga]] in an effort to master its fundamental principles.<ref>{{cite book|last=Syman|first=Stefanie|title=The Subtle Body: The Story of Yoga in America|date=22 June 2010|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-0-374-23676-2|pages= 119–120, 122.}}</ref> On his return to the United States in 1937, his experiences were published across the country over several weeks by the [[North American Newspaper Alliance]] and [[Bell Syndicate]].<ref>Syman, 123.</ref> This was followed by a series of lectures and radio appearances in 1939 and by the publication of the [[memoir]] ''Penthouse of the Gods''.<ref>Hackett, 687-690.</ref> Bernard was also featured in popular magazines, including a cover story in ''[[Family Circle]]'' in 1939, followed shortly by his second book, ''Heaven Lies Within Us'', which explored [[Hatha Yoga]] under the guise of an auto-biography.<ref>Hackett, 695-701</ref> According to 2008's ''Barbarian Lands'', many of the experiences Bernard describes in his books have recently been discovered to have been fabricated, based on the experiences of his father.<ref>Hackett, 694-702.</ref> In 1939, Bernard opened the American Institute of Yoga and Pierre Health Studios.<ref>Hackett, 726-730</ref><ref>Syman, 132</ref>
During the 1940s Bernard completed his [[Ph.D.]] at [[Columbia University]] under the supervision of [[Herbert Schneider (philosopher)|Herbert Schneider]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Life and Works of Theos Bernard|url=http://c250.columbia.edu/c250_celebrates/remarkable_columbians/theos_bernard_scholar.html|website=columbia.edu|publisher=[[Columbia University]]|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>
In 1947, he again visited northern India, on an expedition to the [[Ki monastery]] in Tibet in an attempt to discover special manuscripts. In October, while in an area of Pakistan, Inter-communal violence broke out in the section of the hills that he and his Tibetan companion were travelling. It was reported that both were shot and their bodies thrown in a river.<ref group=Note>This account of the death of Theos Bernard was related by G.A. Bernard, Theos' father</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Bernard|first1=Theos|title=Hatha yoga|date=1982|publisher=Rider|isbn=0091500516|page=vi|edition=Fourth impression of the revised edition (1968)}}</ref> He was declared dead several months later, though his body was never found.<ref>{{cite book|last=Love|first=Robert|title=The Great Oom: The Improbable Birth of Yoga in America|year= 2010|publisher=Viking Adult|isbn=|page= 315}}</ref>
